		%h3
			Tracking Basics
		%p
			We refer to anything you might track such as your weight, your max bench, your calory intake, time you spend sleeping, etc. as a Metric. 
		%p
			When you record or log a value for any Metric, we call that an Observation. So, if you tell Life Meter "My weight is 159". We create an observation with a value of 159 for the metric Weight.
		%p
			You can add any metric to Life Meter simply by observing it.

		%h3
			Metrics
		%p
			You can add a new Metric to track either by simply observing it or explicitly by typing: "track weight". You will find the list of Metrics that Life Meter is tracking for you in the 'Things You're Tracking' menu. 
		%p
			You may want to edit some of your Metrics to give Life Meter more fine-grained control. To do that, simply click 'Things You're Tracking', then select the Metric. You will then see the basic Metric information along with recent observations you have made of that Metric. You can change the title, add a description, or change the units. You may have made a mistake and want to re-assign all the observations of one Metric to another. E.g. let's say you mis-typed a metric name as 'slep' and want to move all 'slep' observations to 'sleep'. Simply select 'sleep' in the Reassign to Metric drop down and hit Update. All slep observations will move to Sleep and slep will be destroyed.
		%p
			%strong
				Aliases
			You may want to add a list of aliases to any new metrics you add. This helps Life Meter's natural language processor understand what you mean. In particular, if you add any activities to track, you'll want to add all the verb forms of those acitivities as aliases. Example: I  want to track my Work Hours. I'd add 'work', 'working', 'worked' as aliases to the 'Work Hours' metric.

